Fallen Marine Security Guards
CATEGORY 1

Marines Security Guards who were killed or died
owing to acts of terrorism or from events directly
related to the protection of US personnel and/or physical properties.

Application for inclusion can be made
Using Recommend an Honor Roll Candidate below

CATEGORY 1
Marines Security Guards who have been killed while on duty, defending the Embassy and personnel.

CATEGORY 2
Marines Security Guards assigned to Post who died in accident or illness.
Former MSGs who have been killed in action during war or conflict.
Former MSGs who've died in Government Service or Law Enforcement
MSGs and Former MSGs who've been awarded Medal of Honor, Navy Cross, Silver Star

CATEGORY 3
Deceased MEGA Association Members

CATEGORY 4
Deceased Former MSGs

(Assistant Secretary of State for Diplomatic Security):
" He was a dedicated professional who was committed to the service of his country. We mourn the loss of Peter, who gave the ultimate sacrifice in this fight for freedom. Peter was killed September 19, 2005 In Mosul Iraq by a suicide bomber. Peter was the driver of the middle vehicle in a U.S. diplomatic motorcade of 3 vehicles. One of Peter's teammates said in an email to us: On the morning that Peter gave his life, I was one of the four that he saved with his move to block the car bomber from the motorcade. If he hadn't made the move that he did, my vehicle would have taken the hit. He died a Hero! "

Kenneth E. Hunt Jr.
Family: Maria (wife), Children: Kenneth III, Kimberly

Died: July 24, 2005 (Gravesite)
Master Sgt. Hunt was providing security as part of a six-vehicle improvised-explosive-device response team with Marine Wing Support Squadron 371 in Al Taqaddam, Iraq. A large explosion near one of the vehicles wounded four Marines, and while the team gave the wounded first aid, Hunt’s vehicle, an armored Humvee, hit an anti-tank mine. Hunt suffered burns to over 60 percent of his body in the explosion. He was medically evacuated to Balad, Iraq, and then transported to Brooke Army Medical Center, Fort Sam Houston, San Antonio, on July 26. Hunt died of cardiac arrest Oct. 12 due to complications from the wounds he received. He is survived by his wife Maria and two children, Kenneth III and Kimberly, all of whom were with him when he died.
USMC:
Marine Security Guard,
1st Battalion, 1st Marines, 1st Marine Division: Heavy machine gunner and squad leader with Weapons Company, ,
3rd Marines of the 1st Marine Division: Machine gun section leader, platoon sergeant and platoon commander.
MCRD San Diego: Drill instructor
1st Battalion / 1st Marines 1st Marine Division: platoon sergeant for the Combined Anti-tank Platoon.
School of Infantry: heavy machine gun instructor at 1st Division schools.
instructor and platoon commander (deployment to Kaunas, Lithuania, cross-trained Lithuanian NCOs small-unit tactics.
Marine Aircraft Group 13 - Yuma ( August 1999), Detachment First Sergeant Personnel Support Detachment , Hunt transferred H&H Squadron : Squadron ground training officer.
MWSS-371 (October 2004), Squadron gunnery sergeant.

Melissa Schmidt
Born: April 18, 1967 Bloomer, Wisconsin
KIA: August 1, 2002
(From Together-we-Served): Officer Schmidt was shot and killed after she and her partner responded to a call reporting a woman with a gun. Contact was made with the 60-year-old female suspect and while the officers were questioning her, she said she needed to go to the bathroom. Officer Schmidt escorted the woman to the public restroom in the lobby of the building. While in the restroom, the woman produced a handgun and opened fire, striking Officer Schmidt in the abdomen below her vest. Officer Schmidt was able to return fire and killed the suspect.
